The issue lies in `app/counter.js`. The `incrementCounter()` function used a non-atomic "read-modify-write" pattern. This means it fetched the value from Redis, performed the addition in memory, and then saved the result back to Redis. When multiple requests were made simultaneously, race conditions occurred, resulting in overlapping updates and therefore "lost increments."

I have refactored `app/counter.js` to utilize Redis's atomic operation `INCR`, which inherently guarantees that operations execute sequentially without race conditions.

```javascript
// Before
async function incrementCounter() {
  const client = createClient();

  // Read current value
  const current = await client.get(COUNTER_KEY);
  const value = parseInt(current || "0", 10);

  // Increment and write back
  const newValue = value + 1;
  await client.set(COUNTER_KEY, newValue.toString());

  logger.debug(`Counter incremented: ${value} -> ${newValue}`);
  return newValue;
}

// After
async function incrementCounter() {
  const client = createClient();

  const newValue = await client.incr(COUNTER_KEY);

  logger.debug(`Counter incremented to ${newValue}`);
  return newValue;
}
```

